Sure 👍 let’s break down Skip() and Take() in Entity Framework with a real-time example you can easily explain in an interview.
🧠 Concept:
Skip(n) → Skips the first n records.
Take(m) → Takes the next m records after skipping.
Together, they are used for pagination — fetching data page by page instead of loading everything at once.
💼 Real-Time Example:
Imagine you’re building an Employee Management System that displays a list of employees on a web page.
Instead of loading all 10,000 employees at once (which is slow 🐢), you show 10 employees per page.
✅ Code Example:
int pageNumber = 2;  // Example: user clicked on page 2 int pageSize = 10;   // Show 10 employees per pagevar employees = context.Employees
                       .OrderBy(e => e.EmployeeId)
                       .Skip((pageNumber - 1) * pageSize)
                       .Take(pageSize)
                       .ToList();
🔍 What happens internally:
Page 1 → Skip(0).Take(10) → Gets employees 1–10
Page 2 → Skip(10).Take(10) → Gets employees 11–20
Page 3 → Skip(20).Take(10) → Gets employees 21–30
⚙️ SQL Generated:
EF translates the LINQ to SQL automatically:
SELECT * FROM EmployeesORDER BY EmployeeIdOFFSET 10 ROWS FETCH NEXT 10 ROWS ONLY;
 
 
